data.content:
Yes — use **tuples** to get type safety and avoid `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Benefits over `object[]`:**
- **Type safety** — compiler catches mismatched types
- **No boxing** for value types like `bool`
- **Named fields** improve readability

> **Note:** Tuple support in `[DynamicData]` requires **MSTest v3.8+**. On older versions, you can use `[DataRow]` for simple inline cases:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

`[DataRow]` works well for compile-time constants. Use `[DynamicData]` with tuples when you need computed values or complex types.
